      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">Polonium is a silvery-grey metal. It is readily dissolved in most acids. At elevated temperatures polonium oxidises to polonium(IV) oxide </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">– Po</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">. </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">It reacts with halogens: the reaction with chlorine produces polonium(II) chloride </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">– PoC</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">l</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0"> - and with iodine, polonium(IV) iodide – Po</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">I</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="0">4</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. Polonium is a very rare, naturally radioactive element. Polonium was discovered by Marie Sklodowska-Curie and Pierre Curie in 1898. It was named after Poland, the native country of Marie Sklodowska-Curie.</text>
   </par>
